default3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultComplaintsdefault3.4.1 
default              
defaultThe Response provides a detailed consideration of the adequacy of the complaints system and concludes that the complaints system is adequate and will in any event be strengthened.  The adeq
defaultuacy of the current complaints system is disputed by 
defaultHer Majesty’s Inspectorate of Prisons (HMIP)
default, the Children’s Commissioner
default, APIL
default and others.  APL research with over 200 prisoners shows that 55 per cent consider the internal prison complaints process to
default be ‘very poor’ with 45 per cent considering the PPO to be ‘very poor’.  Even if the complaints system were to be more effective, it is not an adequate substitute for legal representation.  This is because:
default(i)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe complaints system 
defaultlooks 
defaultbackward, not forward
default, looking whereas legal work that meets the rigorous legal aid sufficient benefit test must be of a practical benefit to the client;
default(ii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe complaints system is limited in ambit – not all the matters currently covered by legal aid will come within the scope o
defaultf the internal complaints system.  For instance, representations to the Justice Secretary about the period between reviews are not a matter 
defaultfor 
defaulta complaint to the prison; nor are concerns about local authority duties to house children on release from priso
defaultn; and
default(iii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Justice Secretary’s plans to improve the complaints system to justify the removal of legal aid implies the system is not adequate; any such changes should take place before 
defaultremoving legal aid is contemplated, and those changes should be subject 
defaultto monitoring and assessment to determine whether they meet the widespread concerns about the efficacy of the system. 
default3.4.2
default              
defaultAs 
defaultLord Justice 
defaultSedley highlights
default in his recent article
default, the 
defaultMinistry
default of Justice appears "seemingly unaware of the way prisoners’ c
defaultlaims are already handled, [and] proposes to take away access to justice for prisoners (including, for instance, children and expectant and new mothers in the prison system), in the belief, which three decades of judicial review have shown to be mistaken, 
defaultthat the prison complaints system and the prisons ombudsman are sufficient for the redress of illegality and unfairness."
