default3.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultJudicial review
default 
default3.11.1
default              
defaultAPL is concerned that proposed changes to judicial review arrangements will mean that it will become virtually impossible for prisoners to 
defaultaccess the Courts when they are the victims of serious abuse by the State and all other attempts to deal with the problem have failed.
default3.11.2
default              
defaultAs has been said by many before, Sir Winston Churchill included, the way a nation treats its prisoners is a mark a
defaultnd measure of its stored up strength and “the sign and proof of the living virtue in it”.  Access to the courts and the protection of the rule of law should be available to all in equal measure.  
default3.11.3
default              
defaultThe APL agree
defaults
default with Stephen Sedley's assertion that 
defaultthe current proposals "undermine judicial review by starving claimants of legal aid on several fronts"
default. 
default3.
default11
default.4
default              
defaultOn a practical level, judicial review is simply not an adequate safety net to justify the removal of 80 per cent of prison law work.  
default3.
default11
default.5
default              
defaultAt present judicial review work arising from prison law issues may be undertaken by firms with either a prison law contract under the ‘associated Community Legal Service’
default (ACLS)
default scheme or a public law contract.  
defaultACLS work enables firms with a prison law co
defaultntract to commence judicial review work on any issue arising from the criminal contract.  The number of cases that can be commenced is not limited.  Firms with public law contracts on the other hand are allocated a 
defaultlimited number of public law matter start
defaults
default (usually around 15)
default. 
defaultOnce the majority of prison law work is removed from scope, it will only be possible for most public law challenges to be commenced by firms with a public law contract, and even then, the number of cases will be limited to the number
default of matter starts. 
defaultThis means
default that access to judicial review for prison law issues other than challenges concerning the legality of parole and adjudication cases 
defaultis finite: once a provider has used up its matter starts, it is not possible to open a legal h
defaultelp file for a new judicial review, regardless of the strength of the case. The Ministry of Justice is not proposing to increase the number of matter starts allocated to public law providers. There is therefore no scope for providers to absorb the prison l
defaultaw cases that will now be forced down the judicial review route as a result of the scope cuts. The effect of this will be that meritorious cases will go unheard and prisoners will be prevented from accessing judicial review. 
default We are not aware of any impact
default assessment on the increased need for public law matter starts based on the removal of criminal legal aid for prison law.
default3.
default11
default.5
default              
defaultIn addition, the future of judicial review is uncertain. In September 2013 the Lord Chancellor published further proposals for 
defaultthe reform of judicial review
default. If enacted, those proposals will reduce the availability of judicial review for individual prisoners and their representative groups by imposing more restrictive rules on standing, forcing providers to work at risk, increasi
defaultng the use of wasted costs orders and limiting the availability of costs protection. In light of this it is impossible to rely on judicial review as protecting the right of access to the courts for prisoners going forward. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCase Study default7defaultH was serving a de
defaultterminate sentence.  H's 5 year old son was diagnosed with a brain tumour and given a very short life expectancy.  The client contacted us seeking advice in relation to his position.  H and the child’s mother wanted to him have as much contact with his son
default as possible.  
defaultH's lawyers made an application to the prison for some form of release / temporary release to facilitate contact.  The prison granted an escorted visit, however, indicated no further visits would be granted.
defaultH's lawyers were ultimately succ
defaultessful after a number of contested hearings and H was granted a schedule of further visits with his son prior to his release from prison. The client was released on licence with similar restrictions on contact with his son.  This was despite his deteriorat
defaulting health and very short life expectancy.  The whole family was anxious for our client to spend as much time as possible with his son.
defaultUnder the new scope criteria....defaultthis issue will be out of scope.
defaultAs the issue arose from a prison law matter, H's lawyer
defaults were able to open an associated Legal Help file in order to challenge the decision not to grant any further home leave.  H's lawyers sent a Letter Before Claim and subsequently issued Judicial Review Proceedings in the High Court for further escorted vis
defaultits.
defaultH's lawyers would have only been able to deal with this case if H's lawyers had enough Public Law Matter Starts left, of which H's lawyers are awarded 15 per year.
defaultWhy not use the complaints system?defaultThe complaints system is currently a very time
default consu
defaultming
default process, H's son was given a very short time to live and this case had to therefore be dealt with as expeditiously as possible. The complaints system would not have dealt with the case quickly enough.
defaultDue to the urgent nature of the case the initial h
defaultearing was granted the day after the application was lodged.  This was before permission was granted and under the proposals the substantial costs of this hearing would be at risk.
defaultNumerous urgent judicial review hearings were necessary, where the barriste
defaultr pushed for them to be granted proper contact. At each hearing the authorities tried to restrict contact. Ultimately the father and son were granted the contact they wanted by the High Court: they were granted more visits and then allowed to see each othe
defaultr every day – they were together on the day the son passed away.
defaultUnder the proposed funding cuts this family would not have had such access to a prison law solicitor. In addition, cuts to family law funding mean they would not have had access to a family law solicitor either.  They would have been powerless in the face 
defaultof the unlawful interference by the authorities in their lives. The mother told everyone that she wanted her son to be able to see his father as much as possible; that she needed the father to be there to support her and the family. Nobody listened to her,
default and nobody would have listened to her if the family had not had access to a solicitor. The government’s proposals threaten all of this.
